===Etymology 1===
From {{der|en|frm|policie}}, from {{der|en|LL.|-}} {{m|la|politia||citizenship; government}}, classical {{der|en|la|polītīa}} (in Cicero), from {{der|en|grc|πολιτεία||citizenship; polis, (city) state; government}}, from {{m|grc|πολίτης||citizen}}. Compare {{doublet|en|police|polity|notext=1}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|~}}

# A [[principle]] of [[behaviour]], [[conduct]] etc. thought to be [[desirable]] or [[necessary]], especially as formally expressed by a [[government]] or other authoritative body. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#: {{ux|en|The Communist Party has a '''policy''' of returning power to the workers.}}
#: {{ux|en|It's company '''policy''' that all mobile phones are forbidden in meetings.}}
# [[wise|Wise]] or [[advantageous]] [[conduct]]; [[prudence]], formerly also with connotations of [[craftiness]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#* {{RQ:Fuller Holy Warre|chapter=King Richard Taken Prisoner in Austria; Sold and Sent to the Emperour; Dearly Ransomed, Returneth Home|page=130|passage=[H]e &#91;{{w|Richard I of England}}&#93; was diſcovered in an inne in Auſtria, becauſe he diſguiſed his perſon not his expenſes; ſo that the very '''policie''' of an hoſteſſe, finding his purſe ſo farre above his clothes, did detect him: {{...}}}}
#* {{RQ:Austen Pride and Prejudice|volume=II|chapter=XI|page=131|passage=These bitter accusations might have been suppressed, had I with greater '''policy''' concealed my struggles, and flattered you into the belief of my being impelled by unqualified, unalloyed inclination; {{...}}}}
# {{lb|en|now|rare}} Specifically, political [[shrewdness]] or (formerly) [[cunning]]; [[statecraft]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#* {{RQ:Marlowe Jew of Malta|I|lines=12-13|text=Ay, ''''policy'''! that's their profession,<br>And not simplicity, as they suggest.}}
#* '''1946''', {{w|Bertrand Russell}}, ''History of Western Philosophy'', I.25:
#*: Whether he believed himself a god, or only took on the attributes of divinity from motives of '''policy''', is a question for the psychologist, since the historical evidence is indecisive.
# {{lb|en|Scotland|now|chiefly|in the plural}} The [[grounds]] of a large country [[house]]. {{defdate|from 18th c.}}
#* {{RQ:Stevenson Kidnapped|text=There was but one thing happened worth narrating; and that is the visit I had of Robin Oig, one of the sons of the notorious Rob Roy. He was sought upon all sides on a charge of carrying a young woman from Balfron and marrying her (as was alleged) by force; yet he stepped about Balquhidder like a gentleman in his own walled '''policy'''.}}
#* '''1955''', {{w|Robin Jenkins}}, ''The Cone-Gatherers'', Canongate 2012, page 36:
#*: Next morning was so splendid that as he walked through the '''policies''' towards the mansion house despair itself was lulled.
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} The art of [[governance]]; [[political science]]. {{defdate|14th–18th c.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 5|act=I|scene=i|pages=69–70|pageref=70|passage=Liſt his diſcourse of Warre; and you ſhall heare / A fearefull Battaile rendred you in Muſique. / Turne him to any Cauſe of '''Pollicy''', / The Gordian Knot of it he will vnlooſe, / Familiar as his Garter: {{...}}}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[state]]; a [[polity]]. {{defdate|14th–16th c.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A set political system; civil administration. {{defdate|15th–19th c.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[trick]]; a [[stratagem]]. {{defdate|15th–19th c.}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Titus Andronicus Q1|act=II|scene=i|page=35|passage=Tis '''pollicie''' and ſtratageme must doo / That you affect, and ſo muſt you reſolue, / That what you cannot as you would [[achieve|atchiue]], / You muſt perforce accompliſh as you may: {{...}}}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} Motive; object; inducement.
#* {{RQ:Sidney Arcadia|chapter=I|page=9|passage=I pray you (said he) honest men, what such right have you in me, as not to suffer me to doe with my self what I list? and what '''pollicie''' have you to bestow a benefite where it is counted an injury?}}

